“Socioeconomic Hardship and Food‐Access Deserts in Five Pennsylvania Counties (2018)” This captures your creation of a composite hardship index and its relationship to food‐desert measures, while clearly noting the geography and year.

library(readxl)
library(dplyr)
library(janitor)

file_path <- "/Users/villatoro/Downloads/INFO_896/CHR_2018.xlsx"

# 1) Read the main “Ranked Measure Data” sheet, keep fips + our two z‑scores
df <- read_xlsx(file_path, sheet="Ranked Measure Data", skip=1, col_names=TRUE) %>%
  clean_names() %>%
  select(
    fips,
    county,
    population,
    z_pov = z_score_119,   # % children in poverty
    z_inc = z_score_126    # income ratio
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    hardship_index_2 = (z_pov + z_inc) / 2
  )

# 3) Compute the state‑wide mean & SD of median household income
stats_med <- add %>%
  summarise(
    mu_med = mean(household_income, na.rm=TRUE),
    sd_med = sd(  household_income, na.rm=TRUE)
  )

# 4) Build z_med for each county
med2 <- add %>%
  # bring in population so we can apply the small‑county cap
  left_join(df %>% select(fips, population), by="fips") %>%
  # attach the scalars
  bind_cols(stats_med) %>%
  mutate(
    # raw z
    z_med_raw = (household_income - mu_med) / sd_med,
    # flip sign so higher income = less hardship
    z_med     = -z_med_raw,
    # missing → average (0)
    z_med     = replace_na(z_med, 0),
    # cap extremes at ±3 for counties with pop < 20k
    z_med     = if_else(population < 20000, pmin(pmax(z_med, -3), 3), z_med)
  ) %>%
  select(fips, z_med)

# 5) Join back on fips and compute the 3‑variable index
hardship3 <- df %>%
  left_join(med2, by="fips") %>%
  mutate(
    hardship_index_3 = rowMeans(across(c(z_pov, z_inc, z_med)), na.rm=TRUE)
  ) %>%
  select(fips, county, population, z_pov, z_inc, z_med, hardship_index_3)

# 2) Join them onto our hardship3 dataframe by FIPS
extended <- hardship3 %>%
  left_join(food, by = "fips")

# 3) (Optional) Standardize those two new measures into z‑scores
stats_food <- extended %>%
  summarise(
    mu_fi = mean(percent_food_insecure,   na.rm=TRUE),
    sd_fi = sd(  percent_food_insecure,   na.rm=TRUE),
    mu_la = mean(percent_limited_access,  na.rm=TRUE),
    sd_la = sd(  percent_limited_access,  na.rm=TRUE)
  )

extended <- extended %>%
  bind_cols(stats_food) %>%
  mutate(
    z_foodinsec_raw = (percent_food_insecure  - mu_fi) / sd_fi,
    z_limit_raw     = (percent_limited_access - mu_la) / sd_la,

    # both “higher = worse” already true, so no sign‑flip
    z_foodinsec = replace_na(z_foodinsec_raw, 0),
    z_limit     = replace_na(z_limit_raw,     0),

    # cap at ±3 for small counties
    z_foodinsec = if_else(population < 20000, pmin(pmax(z_foodinsec, -3), 3), z_foodinsec),
    z_limit     = if_else(population < 20000, pmin(pmax(z_limit,     -3), 3), z_limit),

    # (Optional) Extend our hardship index to include these:
    hardship_index_5 = rowMeans(across(c(z_pov, z_inc, z_med, z_foodinsec, z_limit)),
                                na.rm=TRUE)
  )

# 4) Inspect the result
extended %>%
  select(fips, county, population,
         z_pov, z_inc, z_med,
         percent_food_insecure, percent_limited_access,
         z_foodinsec, z_limit,
         hardship_index_3, hardship_index_5)

#Map Food Insecurity

library(ggplot2)
library(maps)
library(dplyr)

# 1. Define our five counties
five <- c("Centre","Clinton","Huntingdon","Juniata","Mifflin")

# 2. Pull map polygons for PA & filter to those five
pa5 <- map_data("county") %>%
  filter(region == "pennsylvania",
         subregion %in% tolower(five)) %>%
  mutate(county = tools::toTitleCase(subregion))

# 3. Subset our county‐level table to those five
ext5 <- extended %>%
  filter(county %in% five)

# 4. Join map + data
map5 <- pa5 %>%
  left_join(ext5, by = "county")

# 5. Plot
ggplot(map5, aes(long, lat, group = group, fill = percent_food_insecure)) +
  geom_polygon(color = "white", size = 0.3) +
  coord_quickmap() +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(name = "% Food Insecure") +
  labs(
    title = "2018 Food Insecurity in our Five Counties (PA)",
    subtitle = "Centre, Clinton, Huntingdon, Juniata, Mifflin",
    caption  = "Source: CHR_2018.xlsx"
  ) +
  theme_void()

#Scatter-plot food access vs. hardship

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

# Define our five counties
five <- c("Centre","Clinton","Huntingdon","Juniata","Mifflin")

# Subset our extended data to those five
ext5 <- extended %>%
  filter(county %in% five)

# 1) Food Insecurity vs. Hardship
ggplot(ext5, aes(x = hardship_index_3, y = percent_food_insecure)) +
  geom_point(size = 3, color = "tomato") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = TRUE, color = "steelblue") +
  geom_text(aes(label = county), vjust = -1.2, size = 3) +
  labs(
    x = "Composite Hardship Index",
    y = "% Food Insecure",
    title = "2018 Food Insecurity vs. Socioeconomic Hardship",
    subtitle = "Five PA Counties",
    caption = "Data: CHR_2018.xlsx"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()


# 2) Limited Access vs. Hardship
ggplot(ext5, aes(x = hardship_index_3, y = percent_limited_access)) +
  geom_point(size = 3, color = "forestgreen") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_text(aes(label = county), vjust = -1.2, size = 3) +
  labs(
    x = "Composite Hardship Index",
    y = "% Limited Access to Healthy Foods",
    title = "2018 Limited‑Access Food Desert vs. Hardship",
    subtitle = "Five PA Counties",
    caption = "Data: CHR_2018.xlsx"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
